TY  - JOUR
T1  - Influence of Speed of Third-Party Intervention and Outcome on Negotiator and Constituent Fairness Judgments
AU  - Conlon, Donald E.
AU  - Fasolo, Peter M.
Y1  - 1990/12/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256293
DO  - 10.5465/256293
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 833
EP  - 846
VL  - 33
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Using a simulated organizational dispute, we tested the impact of a third-party's intervention on disputants' perceptions of procedural and distributive justice and satisfaction with the third party. We manipulated disputants' roles in the negotiation, the speed of third-party intervention, and the outcome imposed by the third party in a two-by-two-by-five factorial design. The results suggest that the speed of third-party intervention influenced perceptions of procedures more than perceptions of outcomes. Speed of intervention also influenced disputants differently depending on their role. Outcome influenced all measures of procedural and distributive fairness. We discuss implications for managerial behavior in dispute resolution and consequences for the measurement of procedural justice.
AB  - Using a simulated organizational dispute, we tested the impact of a third-party's intervention on disputants' perceptions of procedural and distributive justice and satisfaction with the third party. We manipulated disputants' roles in the negotiation, the speed of third-party intervention, and the outcome imposed by the third party in a two-by-two-by-five factorial design. The results suggest that the speed of third-party intervention influenced perceptions of procedures more than perceptions of outcomes. Speed of intervention also influenced disputants differently depending on their role. Outcome influenced all measures of procedural and distributive fairness. We discuss implications for managerial behavior in dispute resolution and consequences for the measurement of procedural justice.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256293
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256293
