TY  - JOUR
T1  - Interactive Effects of “Type A” Behavior and Perceived Control on Worker Performance, Job Satisfaction, and Somatic Complaints
AU  - Lee, Cynthia
AU  - Ashford, Susan J.
AU  - Bobko, Philip
Y1  - 1990/12/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256296
DO  - 10.5465/256296
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 870
EP  - 881
VL  - 33
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This research examined the moderating role of perceived control on the relations between Type A behavior and worker performance, job satisfaction, and somatic complaints. Results suggest that people with high levels of Type A behavior who also have high perceived control perform better and have greater job satisfaction than those low in perceived control. However, the former also reported more somatic complaints than the latter. Implications of our findings and directions for future research are discussed.
AB  - This research examined the moderating role of perceived control on the relations between Type A behavior and worker performance, job satisfaction, and somatic complaints. Results suggest that people with high levels of Type A behavior who also have high perceived control perform better and have greater job satisfaction than those low in perceived control. However, the former also reported more somatic complaints than the latter. Implications of our findings and directions for future research are discussed.
